Since the roots of the Gay Liberation Movement and the Stonewall uprising, the struggle of LGBTQ+ (lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, queer and related identities) rights has transformed from social movement to global tourism event (World Tourism Organization, 2017). Nowadays, pride festivals are one of the well-known festivals across the world, which have attracted millions of people each year and have considerable economic gains to the destinations (InterPride, 2016; Waitt, Markwell, & Gorman-Murray, 2008). Many countries and destinations around the world position themselves as gay or LGBTQ+ friendly. The tourism and hospitality sector views LGBTQ+ individuals, especially the ‘educated’, ‘white’, ‘wealthy’ and ‘bourgeois’ gays – as a consumption group generally attending pride festivals, attracted to gay-friendly bars or clubs (Diekmann & Smith, 2015). Cities supporting LGBTQ+ rights such as Amsterdam, Stockholm, and Copenhagen give particular importance to LGBTQ+ individuals in tourism marketing (such as Amsterdam Marketing) with the effect of the “pink economy” (Vorobjovas-Pinta & Hardy, 2015
                     , p. 410–411). This situation causes a paradoxical structure while the mainstream attitude of the sector, which seems to support LGBTQ+ rights but also degrades LGBTQ+ individuals to a consumption market, normalizes gayness under the influence of neoliberal policies and creates a hierarchy among LGBTQ+ individuals (Waitt et al., 2008
                     ). Such a paradoxical nature of pride festivals brings along some critical questions: Has the movement's focus shifted to festival and tourism as if there has been significant progress in LGBTQ+ lives worth celebrating? Is the festival itself political fun?

Pride festivals are crucial for the LGBTQ+ movement since it helps to gain “social capital” (Putnam, 2000
                     ). This capital provides a bridge between the LGBTQ+ community and the broader society by creating a sense of individual identity (Tilly, 2005
                     ). Furthermore, within the context of pride festivals, groups (both LGBTQ+ and supporters of the movement) want to demonstrate their strength in terms of being visible and proud. Thus, the festival helps groups raise their demands and voice their ignored existence regarding equality towards state and society (Holzhacker, 2012
                     ). Also, the pride festival includes marketing activities in which many companies sponsor that event, and the participants are the consumption group during the festival. For this reason, our research focuses on the contribution of Amsterdam Pride to both gender equality and responsible consumption that refers to “the continued act of controlling desire by avoiding extravagant purchases and rationalized use of goods and services that satisfy basic needs” (Quoquab & Mohammad, 2020
                     , p. 311). Furthermore, we argue that consumption should be responsible because the perspective of responsible consumption focuses on improving the quality of life for both individuals and society by considering human rights and social justice (Salonen, 2013
                     ). Thus, we can demonstrate the contribution of the Amsterdam Pride to the sustainable development goals of the United Nations (particularly SDG 5 and SDG 12).

The article fills a gap in the mainstream festival and event management literature that does not address gender-based power dynamics. This can be partly explained by the resistance to adopt poststructuralist queer arguments and challenge the hetero-patriarchal order in the mainstream literature (Ferguson & Alarcón, 2015). In addressing the aforementioned gap in the literature and responding to several calls voiced in critical tourism scholarship (e.g. Figueroa-Domecq, Pritchard, Segovia-Pérez, Morgan, & Villacé-Molinero, 2015; Ong et al., 2021; Pritchard & Morgan, 2017
                     ; Reimer & Walter, 2013
                     ; Scheyvens, 2007
                     ), this paper contributes to a growing body of knowledge within mainstream festival and event management literature as an area considered largely to be “queer-blind”. Even though SDG studies consider gender equality, they predominantly focus on white and heterosexual women (Nwangwu & Ezeibe, 2019
                     ; Struckmann, 2018
                     ). Such a limitation demonstrates a need to create a more inclusionary approach to understanding gender equality. For this reason, this paper focuses on the complex nature of gender-based as well as consumption-based relationships in the context of the Amsterdam Pride Festival.

In the tourism literature, the tourism mobility of LGBTQ+ individuals is conceptualized with different terms such as gay tourism, lesbian tourism, LGBT tourism, and queer tourism and centred around gay individuals, while gay tourism
