                           Gay tourism is used in some sources for both gay and lesbian tourists. During the literature review on LGBTQ+ tourism, no study was found that particularly focused on the tourism mobility of bisexual, transgender and intersex individuals. In this paper the term gay/gay tourism are used in the context which is used in the literature. Because the tourism market mainly prefers gay and gay tourism categorisation as it has focused primarily on the gay segment.
                         is the most common usage (Holcomb & Luongo, 1996; Pritchard, Morgan, & Sedgley, 1998; Waitt & Markwell, 2014
                        ). Gay tourists are particularly considered a niche market and defined by the positive economic impacts they bring to the destinations they travel to, such as Spain and Netherlands (Holcomb & Luongo, 1996; Pritchard et al., 1998
                        ; UNWTO, 2017). The perception that LGBTQ+ individuals are a consumption group has given rise to a new heteronormative myth called the pink economy that gays and lesbians are affluent and travel a lot (Badgett, 2001
                        ; Waitt & Gorman-Murray, 2011
                        ). This Western-centric myth creates a perception that LGBTQ+ gender identity and sexual orientation occur within certain performances (Padilla, 2007
                        ).

Gay-friendly marketing emphasised in national tourism marketing strategies normalizes gayness through a gay identity created in accordance with heteronormativity within the framework of neoliberal policies (Waitt et al., 2008
                        ). Such a normalisation of physically healthy and “good” looking gay bodies creates sensitivities and concerns within the community. This situation paves the way for developing phobic behaviours and vulnerabilities against those who do not fit into these categories. In contrast to gays who experience gay-friendly organisations and destinations serving in the gay tourism market (as a consumption strategy), lesbian, bisexual and transgender tourists, for instance, encounter homophobic, biphobic and transphobic behaviour in many tourism organisations, especially in hotels (Enguix, 2017
                        ; Poria, 2006
                        ; Puar, 2002a, 2002b). The LGBTQ+ market, in general, ostracises lesbian, bisexual and transgender individuals and those with weak economic purchasing power within the community, thereby creating a market based on gender and class discrimination and presenting gays as a normal niche consumer group in some destinations (Chasin, 2000a
                        ; Enguix, 2017
                        ). This shows us how neoliberal policies shape the commodification of sexuality and transform the LGBTQ+ lifestyle into a consumerist activity (Wolf, 2009
                        ). According to Waitt et al. (2008, p. 795), this approach is not a negative but a wrong practice of the heteronormative order.

As mega-events, LGBTQ+ festivals are a driving force in international LGBTQ+ tourism (Waitt & Markwell, 2014
                        ). As a community that organizes many events ranging from small parties to festivals, the LGBTQ+ community is no stranger to these events. LGBTQ+ festivals occupy a broad place in gay tourism and event/festival tourism and have an extremely important attraction for destinations (Waitt & Markwell, 2014
                        ). It can thus be said that pride festivals, which are the most visible and dynamic component of LGBTQ+ tourism (Southall & Fallon, 2011
                        ), are shaped within the framework of capitalism's hegemony of consumption (Kates & Belk, 2001
                        ). Contrary to their historical and political content, pride festivals have today been incorporated into the production-consumption system of tourism and entered into a process in which identity is constructed with a focus on consumption (Chasin, 2000b
                        ; Wolf, 2009
                        ). LGBTQ+ festivals have thus come to be among the major tourist attractions (Taylor, 2014
                        ). Furthermore, the promotion of festivals can affect the setting of festivals, even motivations of participants like in Michigan Womyn's Festival (Browne, 2009
                        ).

The connection between pride festivals and tourism has stimulated some questioning and criticism. There are views that festivals have become commodified and assimilated, departed from their ideology, and lost their authenticity (Taylor, 2014
                        ). The concept of authenticity, which is used in tourism literature from different perspectives such as objective (MacCannell, 1999
                        ), constructive (Cohen, 2004
                        ), postmodern and existential authenticity (Wang, 1999
                        ), is an abstract, subjective and perceptual concept. Thus the meaning of the concept varies according to the perspective that it is related. In terms of LGBTQ+ festivals, it refers to an individual's search for her/his own being as existential authenticity (Wang, 1999
                        ). Pride festivals allow LGBTQ+ tourists to experience their own state of being in communitas that she/he encounters and feels a sense of unity (Kaygalak-Celebi, Kaya, Ozeren, & Gunlu-Kucukaltan, 2020). However, this type of authenticity is used for commercial purposes and creates new spaces and identities. As Hartal and Sasson-Levy (2021) argue, neoliberalism and the politics of gay tourism marketing present Tel Aviv and local Mizrahi culture as exotic and different. By the time of progress in Tel Aviv, gay Mizrahi culture was perceived as authentic both by tourists and locals. Hence, the new type of the authentic self is questionable (Hartal & Sasson-Levy, 2021) as this search for authenticity is a symbolic, not concrete, search because of commodification (Garzian, 2011
                        ).

Companies that sponsor pride festivals to sell their commodities to the LGBTQ+ market are the central target of these criticisms (Wolf, 2009
                        ). Markwell and Waitt (2009) argue that the change in pride festivals is an ideological transformation and due to financial sponsorships. Many large companies attempt exploitation using rainbow colours and use pride festivals as a show of economic strength (Kates, 2003
                        ; Kates & Belk, 2001
                        ; Wolf, 2009
                        ). This is especially cited as the reason for the commodification of pride festivals and the shift away from the struggle-and resistance-based focus since the 1990s (Chasin, 2000a
                        ). Table 1
                         presents the relevant criticisms in the literature.

The study's sample size consists of 40 self-identified LGBTQ+ participants who attended the Amsterdam Pride in 2017. The sample size can be considered relatively high when taken into account the qualitative research paradigm (Creswell & Poth, 2018
                        ) and sexual and gender minority people as being relatively difficult to access. (Please see Table 2 in the Annex for further information about the participants). Firstly, we adopted criterion sampling as one of the purposeful sampling strategies in qualitative research tradition (Emmel, 2013
                        ; Palinkas et al., 2015
                        ; Patton, 2002
                        ). The criterion was utilized to distinguish festival visitors (either domestic or foreign tourists) from local people. In this respect, we only included tourists as participants rather than local people who voluntarily accepted to be interviewed, having been totally informed about the scope of the research. Secondly, we adopted snowball sampling to access other participants who generally attend the event with their friends and partners. The main limitation of the sample is not to have diverse age groups. For this reason, the number of senior participants is low. However, since we do not collect evidence from the field regarding the difference between previous and current LGBTQ+ events, age does not seem to be the primary factor within the context of this research. Nevertheless, future research can consider ageing issues and collect data from senior participants in comparing the current and previous LGBTQ+ events from a historical and critical perspective.

We conducted an inductive thematic content analysis to arrive at critical and interpretive conclusions drawing on in-depth interviews as well as participant observation to ensure data triangulation for reflexive inquiry (Creswell, 2013
                        ). In the data analysis stage, we firstly performed pilot coding in the light of the research questions and coding frame. Then, we checked the consistency of the categories and subcategories shaped by the codes and discussed differently coded subcategories with our research team members who shared their individual, independent assessment. Next, we analysed and coded the interview transcripts multiple times by each author separately. Later on, the research team met several times to discuss the initial codes to decide about subcategories and themes. We revised the subcategories accordingly and arrived at a coding consistency of 90% (Schreier, 2012
                        , p. 147, Schreier, 2014, p. 179). Indeed, utilising multiple coders is a commonly used technique to increase trustworthiness in qualitative research (Elo et al., 2014
                        ). At last, we generated final themes through one more discussion round by figuring out the common and emerging patterns across the entire data. Based on Corbin and Strauss (2015) three stages in qualitative data analysis that are ‘open coding’, ‘axial coding’ and ‘selective coding’, the data set was subject to inductive and thematic analysis supported by a critical and deconstructive approach (Gehman et al., 2018
                        ; Gioia, Corley, & Hamilton, 2013). The consent form, the semi-structured interview guide and the list of research themes and subcodes can be found in the Appendix.

As it is understood from the remarks above, the participants feel uneasy about the appearance of the Pride as a festival focused on partying, entertainment and consumption and suggest that it has lost its spirit of social movement. They think that an event in a festive mood cannot have any meaning for LGBTQ+ rights and freedoms. Several other studies, albeit limited, have shown that researchers and interviewees have similar concerns about LGBTQ+ events (Hughes, 2006a
                        ; Hughes, 2006b
                        ; Johnston, 2005
                        ; Richardson, 2017
                        ). Nancy stated that LGBTQ+ issues other than the festival still persist in the Netherlands. A similar finding is also true for the ChillOut Festival. The festival places that defy or appear to challenge heteronormativity during the festival resume reproducing mainstream norms once the festival ends (Waitt & Gorman-Murray, 2011
                        ).

Accordingly, Amsterdam Pride plays a critical role in facilitating the reversal and demolition of homophobic, biphobic and transphobic attitudes towards LGBTQ+ individuals and the acceptance and perception of LGBTQ+ individuals as ‘normal’ by the heteronormative society. Even though Amsterdam Pride contributes to the voice and visibility of LGBTQ+ individuals, the positive impact of pride is limited in the geographical borders that have LGBTQ+ rights. Also, as Browne and Bakshi (2011) highlight, geography has a critical role in discussing LGBTQ+ pride since some regions, such as Russia, criminalize LGBTQ+ individuals (Suchland, 2018
                        ). However, pride events still raise the freedom and rights of LGBTQ+ individuals in front of international audiences through the tools of social media and mass media. Also, the pride creates a highly diverse environment since everyone who supports LGBTQ+ equality attends it. This environment has a critical role in terms of providing an opportunity to give the message of equality for everyone to wider audiences. The festival opposes the heteronormative oppression that LGBTQ+ individuals are subjected to in everyday life and offers LGBTQ+ individuals a place where they feel free to express themselves through fun in the pride rather than protests. Also, since the participants of this pride have been considered as a consumer group by companies that are the sponsors of many events in the festival, the commercial activities have a transformative role in terms of creating an environment that includes fun rather than protests in terms of providing voice and visibility of LGBTQ+ individuals. For this reason, the aforementioned interlink between LGBTQ+ pride and commercial pride reveals a sustainable role for gender equality. The findings of this study are in line with those of previous studies indicating that pride festivals have created transformative outcomes for LGBTQ+ communities (Hughes, 2006a, 2006b; Johnston & Waitt, 2015
                        ; Kates, 2003
                        ; Kates & Belk, 2001
                        ).

The participants criticise from many points of view that Pride has turned to be a consumption practice. The first criticism is against those who attend the festival only for entertainment purposes without knowing the origins and history of the LGBTQ+ struggle. Although the literature embodies many criticisms of pride festivals, no such finding has been reported. The participants think that the festival has departed from its original meaning and been reduced to an entertainment event due to tourism. The primary reason why the festival is held has been forgotten (Getz, 2007
                        ). However, based on the perspective of responsible consumption, the festival benefits the local economy because it creates more job opportunities for local people and the social integration of the workers. The second criticism is against the companies sponsoring the festival. The participants consider that sponsors are attempting exploitation using rainbow colours, as noted in the earlier studies (Kates, 2003
                        ; Kates & Belk, 2001
                        ; Wolf, 2009
                        ). However, using rainbow colours makes LGBTQ+ individuals visible in public. For this reason, consuming products of the sponsoring companies contributes to consciousness regarding gender equality. The third criticism is that these events address only western, middle- and upper-class white gays through the normalisation strategies of neoliberal policies and cause LGBTQ+ individuals to shift away from the original grassroots and assimilate (Markwell & Waitt, 2009
                        ; Taylor, 2014
                        ). Even though there is such criticism, this situation contributes to the awareness of gender equality through creating inclusionary perspectives for LGBTQ+ individuals in society. Thus, its progress and the other issues related to discrimination within the same group will be the next agendas for gender equality studies.

The pink economy myth paradoxically portrays LGBTQ+ bodies as both ‘normal’ and ‘abnormal’ (Butler, 1990
                        ). Those individuals have been transformed into consuming subjects as a niche market. Being a subject is a criticism against the heteronormative perspective within the framework of collective recognition, while it also creates a homonormative perspective (Costa, 2008
                        ). As a matter of fact, the spotlighting of gay bodies at the pride causes homonormativity, resulting in the exclusion of non-cisgender individuals. For example, the uniform, muscular gay male bodies are used as an icon for advertising in most places during the festival to attract more visitors and make them spend more which limits the visibility of non-cisgender identities as well as other minority members within the community (e.g. black and minority ethnic LGBTQ+ groups). As some participants attending the Amsterdam Pride questioned their belonging to pride, a similar situation was also observed in different contexts and addressed in the studies by Waitt and Stapel (2011) and De Jong (2017) on Sydney Mardi Gras Festival. Moreover, certain body representations (so called ‘aesthetic’ and privileged) are consciously foregrounded in the heteronormative system due to commercial concern.

The aforementioned situation leads to some questioning and discussion about the participants' sense of belonging that deserves further exploration from the viewpoint of fulfilling SDGs of inclusivity in events (Ong et al., 2021). Feeling included in the Pride, albeit given diverse sexualities and representations in the LGBTQ+ community, can be a critical form of belonging. Pride as an event has an important role by offering a possibility for diverse sexualities and identities to band together to echo their ignored existence to achieve social inclusion and contribute to the development of sustainable communities. This is in line with Goal 5 (Gender Equality) and Goal 10 (Reduced Inequalities) to reduce inequality and promote social, economic and political inclusion of people regardless of their age, sex, disability, race, ethnicity, origin, religion or economic or another status (United Nations, 2021
                        ). As can be seen, despite the fact that there is no explicit emphasis on sexual orientation and gender identity, SDGs highlight the inclusive societies with the ultimate aim of ensuring “no one is left behind” (United Nations, 2014
                        , p. 9). We can argue that this agenda set the challenging goals in front of the whole nations to tackle the root causes of structural inequalities and discrimination without having the need to openly declare the socially and historically marginalised status of sexual and gender minorities, which itself is a significant void in the SDGs.

Considering the nature and characteristics of the Pride festival, the aforementioned changes are not unique to Amsterdam Pride. Similar politics and changes such as internal power dynamics within the LGBTQ+ community have happened in the west as well as other places (such as the study by Hartal (2019) on gay tourism to Tel-Aviv), particularly in the last two decades (De Jong, 2017; Kenttamaa Squires, 2019). This situation is very much connected to larger shifts of complex processes of commodification (De Jong, 2017), homonormativity (Brown, 2012
                        ), and rising waves of neoliberal discourses based on consumption in the globalised world (Duggan, 2002
                        ; Puar, 2002a, 2002b). Amsterdam Pride can be a vivid example of an almost global process in this context.

Even though Amsterdam Pride, which entered a new era in 2017 with the changes in the name and event visuals, aims at adopting a more inclusive and holistic approach towards LGBTQ+ individuals, it fails to cover all strands of sexual orientation and gender identity since the elements of the predominantly white, middle-and upper-class, idealised gay body image still stand out in the festival's content. This clearly shows that Amsterdam Pride, like other LGBTQ+ tourism practices, maintains the homonormative system by constructing a gay and lesbian identity (Markwell & Waitt, 2015
                        ; Puar, 2002a, 2002b; Waitt & Gorman-Murray, 2008
                        ). The findings of this research raise the issue regarding two dimensions for gender equality. The first is equality between sexual identities (e.g., homosexuality and heterosexuality). The second is equality within sexual identities (e.g., gay, lesbian and transgender). The first phase of Amsterdam Pride focuses on sustainable gender equality between sexual identities since there is a lack of consciousness regarding gender roles. However, pride still is not successful in terms of overcoming the dominant heterosexist approach in society, and this situation creates an obstacle for both visibility and normalisation of sexual minorities in the social field. Then the second phase of the pride focuses on sustainable gender equality within sexual identities. Yet, participants perceive the pride as a gay dominant festival. For this reason, even if Amsterdam pride aims to promote gender equality by creating a holistic, sustainable and more inclusionary approach to all participants and the gender identities, it still fails to address the issues regarding gender identities. The main reason for this claim comes from the nature of Amsterdam Pride that focuses on LGBTQ+ tourism practices and locates in a liberal country with the participation of individuals around the world.

The mainstream festival activities focus mostly on contributing to the social, economic and cultural development of a region that hosts the festival events (Chang & Hsieh, 2017
                     ). The success of such events is commonly evaluated based on their economic contribution to event stakeholders, the community and the region (Dimmock & Tiyce, 2001
                     ). In this regard, the main stakeholders are the residents in the community-based festivals. However, theme-based festivals such as Amsterdam Pride highlight a social impact through creating visibility and voice for LGBTQ+ individuals. The process of creating visible pride festivals started with the harmful stereotypes produced by the traditional media, which was recognized as allies in the struggles for civil rights (Rosa, Magalhães, Rodríguez-Castro, & Lopez, 2018
                     ). Following this stage, the first years of pride events focused on representing gay individuals and the binary of homo/hetero. Thus, this process demonstrates that pride has progressed in terms of visibility and voice of sexual identities. Even though the several findings of this research highlight similar concerns, such as recognising pride as a gay-based event, it also shows that pride provides the sustainability of gender equality (SDG 5) and responsible consumption (SDG 12) through cognitive impacts of sustainable tourism. The festivals have positive impacts that can cover increasing business and job opportunities, promoting regional culture and history (Song, Xing, & Chathoth, 2015). Also, theme-based festivals such as the Amsterdam Pride in our research provide sustainability of visibility and voice in gender equality. However, the findings of this research are limited to Amsterdam Pride. Since some countries either ban pride parades and criminalize the LGBTQ+ identity or blame LGBTQ+ individuals as having immoral behaviour, contextual differences create critical complexities for Pride events (Suchland, 2018
                     ). For this reason, Amsterdam Pride is a unique event within the context of this research. Pride events organised in Australia, USA and Israel, have been subject to several scholarly inquiries; however, we know relatively little about such events in Europe. This is one of the first crucial attempts to address the embodied approach to Amsterdam Pride, drawing on the 40 LGBTQ+ participants' accounts qualitatively in the light of sustainable development goals, particularly SDG 5 and SDG 12. Further research may concentrate on ‘LGBTQ+ friendly’ destinations and non-LGBTQ+ friendly contexts where Pride events are jeopardised. One cannot assume that the reflections of Amsterdam Pride that was studied in this study can be generalisable across all destinations given the massive disparities in Global North Prides- which are differently funded and politicised.

Building on the queer and critical tourism scholarship, this study highlights the embodied approach to Amsterdam Pride. We can see that LGBTQ+ people see the event as a space for showing off their “normality”. The homonormativity is further strengthened by neoliberalism and ‘a depoliticised event anchored in consumption’ (Duggan, 2002
                     , p. 50). This leads to several disputes within the LGBTQ+ community itself on normalisation and sexual citizenship arguments. In this regard, the focus of Amsterdam Pride as a major tourism activity and attraction is positioned into ‘party’ and ‘entertainment’ rhetoric (Enguix, 2017
                     ; Johnston, 2005
                     ; Rushbook, 2005
                     ) and pinkwashing (Johnston, 2001
                     ; Kama & Ram, 2020
                     ) that complicates its politically embodied meanings (Hughes, 2006b
                     ).

Moreover, as non-LGBTQ+ people attend more and more of the Amsterdam Pride, the subjects of Pride are overshadowed, which is another sign of assimilation of movement (Abrahamson, 2014
                     ; Taylor, 2014
                     ). The depoliticised nature of the event itself is highly ‘political’ that serves the purpose of neoliberal economy and consumer culture. Nevertheless, the changes in the festival clearly demonstrate that Amsterdam Pride has been trying to overcome these problems. Along with the change of the name, the visuals of the 2017 festival were also changed with an intention to make them more inclusive. Thus, Amsterdam Pride has incorporated more inclusive bodily visuals rather than uniform body representations, thereby opening more spaces for queer bodies and fighting against the heteronormative emphasis on normality. This development better reflects the spirit and symbol of the movement, i.e., rainbow, because Amsterdam Pride is also attended by tourists of different ethnicities, bodily forms, sexual orientations, and gender identities. If Amsterdam, known as a gay-friendly destination, reflects its inclusive approach throughout all festival events to a greater extent, it will stimulate authentic feelings and sensations among participants. Thus, Amsterdam can also become a destination of choice not only for LGBTQ+ individuals but also for people from all walks of life who value equality and diversity.
